Ludovic s'accusait et se dsesprait, il rejetait sur lui la responsabilit de cette rechute, et parlait de suivre la jeune fille si elle n'en rchappait pas. Il demandait pardon au doc-teur de n'avoir pas mieux suivi ses conseils et offrait de quitter la chambre afin de ne pas compromettre de nouveau les effets de son traitement. Mais celui-ci avait rflchi, et cette fois son avis fut tout oppos. -Non, lui dit-il, restez. -Mais si je commets encore quelque imprudence ? -Restez, vous dis-je, le mal est fait. Votre prsence a amen une crise, votre absence en amnerait une autre, plus fcheuse encore. Je ne connaissais pas cette enfant c'est une tte de fer. Il faut que vous soyez l, quand elle reprendra ses sens. Restez. -J'obis alors. -Et que le ciel vous inspire, Ludovic, quand le moment sera venu. Cette jeune fille a au coeur une plaie dont je ne puis la gurir et que la Facult en corps ne gurirait pas c'est le dgot de la vie. Tchez d'en venir  bout et j'incli-nerai ma science devant la vtre. L'aimez-vous ? -Si je l'aime ! Vous me demandez si je l'aime ! Ne le voyez-vous pas ? -Eh bien ! alors, il y a quelque chance pour que vous russissiez. Mais, ou je me trompe fort, ou ce sera une cure difficile. Cet entretien avait lieu  voix si basse, que rien n'en pou-vait parvenir aux oreilles de Marguerite, et, pourtant, il se fit chez elle un mouvement singulier. 221 The matter: The king was very glad hereof and caused the combatants to be brought before him. To whom he said, "Gentlemen, to save the blood of you all, I have found a way, and yet the controversy shall be ended that is now amongst you. Are you contented to stand to his judgment that I shall appoint?" They all answered that they were. Then were they bid to return three days after. 

In that time, Fryer Bacon had caused the body of their deceased father to be taken out of the ground and brought to the court. The body he did cause to be bound to a stake, naked to the middle upwards, and likewise prepared three bows and shafts for the three brothers. All these kept he secretly. 

The third day being come, came these three brothers, to whom Fryer Bacon in the presence of the king gave the three bows and shafts, saying, "Be not offended at what I have done. There is no other way but this to judge your cause. See, here is the body of your dead father. Shoot at him, for he that cometh nearest to his heart shall have all the lands and goods." 

The two eldest prepared themselves and shot at him, and stuck their arrows in his breast. Then they bid the youngest to shoot but he refused, saying, "I will rather lose all than wound that body that I so loved while living. Had you ever had but half that love in you to him that I have, you would rather have had your own bodies mangled than to suffer his lifeless corpse thus to be used - nay, you do not only suffer it, but you are the actors of this act of shame." And speaking this, he wept.

In that time, Fryer Bacon had caused the body of their deceased father to be taken out of the ground and brought to the court. The body he did cause to be bound to a stake, naked to the middle upwards, and likewise prepared three bows and shafts for the three brothers. All these kept he secretly. 

The third day being come, came these three brothers, to whom Fryer Bacon in the presence of the king gave the three bows and shafts, saying, "Be not offended at what I have done. There is no other way but this to judge your cause. See, here is the body of your dead father. Shoot at him, for he that cometh nearest to his heart shall have all the lands and goods." 

The two eldest prepared themselves and shot at him, and stuck their arrows in his breast. Then they bid the youngest to shoot but he refused, saying, "I will rather lose all than wound that body that I so loved while living. Had you ever had but half that love in you to him that I have, you would rather have had your own bodies mangled than to suffer his lifeless corpse thus to be used - nay, you do not only suffer it, but you are the actors of this act of shame." And speaking this, he wept.

ocr.region: OF FRIER RUSH. 295 whereat his master had great marvade then they sate downe to breakfast, which being ended they went home, and did such thinges as were there to bee done when his dame sawe that he had so soone ended his busines, she thought that he was a profitable servant, and said Httle but let him alone. In the evening Rush de maunded of his master what hee should doe the next morrow ? his master appointed him twice so much as hee did the day before, which Rush refused not, but got up earely in the morning, and went to the field, and about his worke so soone as his master was ready, he tooke his man's breakfast and came to the field, thinking to helpe Rush but he was no sooner come from his house but the Priest came to see his wife, and presently shee made ready some good meate for them to be merry withall, and whyle it was a dressing, they sate sporting together, who had beene there should have seene many loving touches. And when the goodman came to the field, he found that Rush had done aU that which he appointed, whereof he had great marvade then they sate dovroe to breakfast, and as they sate together, Rush beheld his master's shoone, and perceived that for fault of greasing they were very hard then said Rush to his master, why are not your shooes better greased ? I marvade that you can goe in them, they be so hard, have you no more at home ? Ves, said his master, I have another payre lying under a great chest at home in my chamber. Then said Rush I wdl goe home and grease them that you may put them on to-morrow and

OF FRIER RUSH. 295: At which his master greatly marveled, then they sat down to breakfast. Having finished, they went home and did such things as needed to be done there. When his wife saw that he had so soon ended his business, she thought him a profitable servant, and said little but left him alone. In the evening, Rush asked his master what he should do the next day. His master assigned him twice as much work as he had done the day before, which Rush accepted without complaint. He got up early in the morning and went to the field. As soon as his master was ready, he took his man's breakfast and came to the field, intending to help Rush. However, the moment he left his house, the Priest came to see his wife, and she prepared some good food for them to enjoy together. While it was being prepared, they sat playfully together, demonstrating many loving gestures.

When the man came to the field, he discovered that Rush had already completed all the tasks assigned to him, causing great marvel. Then they sat down to breakfast. While they were eating together, Rush noticed the hardness of his master's shoes, which hadn't been properly greased. He asked, "Why haven't your shoes been better greased? I marvel that you can even walk in them, as they are so hard. Do you not have more at home?" "Yes," replied his master, "I have another pair lying under a great chest at home in my chamber." Rush then offered, "I will go home and grease them, so you may wear them tomorrow.

OF FRIER RUSH. 295: At which his master greatly marveled, then they sat down to breakfast. Having finished, they went home and did such things as needed to be done there. When his wife saw that he had so soon ended his business, she thought him a profitable servant, and said little but left him alone. In the evening, Rush asked his master what he should do the next day. His master assigned him twice as much work as he had done the day before, which Rush accepted without complaint. He got up early in the morning and went to the field. As soon as his master was ready, he took his man's breakfast and came to the field, intending to help Rush. However, the moment he left his house, the Priest came to see his wife, and she prepared some good food for them to enjoy together. While it was being prepared, they sat playfully together, demonstrating many loving gestures.

When the man came to the field, he discovered that Rush had already completed all the tasks assigned to him, causing great marvel. Then they sat down to breakfast. While they were eating together, Rush noticed the hardness of his master's shoes, which hadn't been properly greased. He asked, "Why haven't your shoes been better greased? I marvel that you can even walk in them, as they are so hard. Do you not have more at home?" "Yes," replied his master, "I have another pair lying under a great chest at home in my chamber." Rush then offered, "I will go home and grease them, so you may wear them tomorrow.

ocr.region: OF FRIER RUSH. 271 the space of seaven yeares, and did right well, and every man bad him in love and favour. Then it fortuned upon a day the Priour and his brethren were assembled together in a generaU counsaile, and as they stood talking together, the Priour remembered Rush, and anon he said unto his brethren Friends we have here Rush which is our maister Cooke in our kitchin, and be is an olde servant, and much diligent and true service he hath done to us, and he hath continued among us longer then any servant that ever wee had wherefore me thinke it reason, that hee were promoted into some other office, and made a brother among us. Then all the whole Covent with one voice said they were content it should so be. So the Priour sent for Rush, and when he was come before him and aU bis brethren, the Priour said, Rush it is so, thou hast beene here a long season, and we have found thee hitherto a true and diligent servant, wherefore wee wdl that thou be promoted, and take upon thee an habite as we have, and to become a brother among us. Rush answered and said my Maisters I thanke you aU, and then the Priour gave Rush an habite, and put it on his backe, and so Rush became a brother in the place, neverthelesse he kept his office stiU. prediction.region: OF FRIAR RUSH. 271 For the space of seven years, he performed excellently, and everyone held him in love and favor. Then it happened upon a day the Prior and his brethren were assembled together in a general council. As they stood talking together, the Prior remembered Rush, and promptly said unto his brethren, "Friends, we have here Rush, who is our master cook in our kitchen. He is an old servant, and he has done much diligent and true service for us. He has continued among us longer than any servant we have ever had; therefore, I think it is reasonable that he be promoted to some other office and made a brother among us." Then all the whole convent, with one voice, said they were content it should be so. So the Prior sent for Rush, and when he came before him and all his brethren, the Prior said, "Rush, you have been here a long season, and we have found you to be a true and diligent servant. Therefore, we wish for you to be promoted and take upon you a habit as we have, and become a brother among us." Rush answered and said, "My Masters, I thank you all." Then the Prior gave Rush a habit and put it on his back, and so Rush became a brother in the place, nevertheless, he kept his office still. How Friar Rush made Truncheons for the Friars to fight with. When Rush had on the habit of a Friar and was a brother in the place, he had more vacation days.

ocr.sentence: CE QU'ON PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE.
ocr.region: CE QU'ON PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE. 251 comme une exception parmi le commun des hommes, et que vous tiez ce qu'ils sont tous, perfides et trompeurs  l'occasion. Quand je relevai la tte, l'obscurit la plus complte salait faite dans votre logement, et une lueur d'espoir tra-, versa mon esprit. Point de doute vous alliez venir, vous alliez paratre. Nulle puissance humaine ne m'et contrainte  croire que vous passeriez la journe sans me voir et sans tenir la promesse que vous m'aviez faite. Vous tiez-donc en. chemin j'en tais convaincue comme d'un article de foi. En - effet, la sonnette retentit quelqu'un tait l. - Ab 1 enfin, m'criai-je, le voici Dieu soit lou ! Je courus vers la porte et ouvris. C'tait Melchior. XXVI Je ne chercherai pas, Ludovic,  vous raconter ce que j'prouvai  la vue de cet homme. Ce fut un sentiment si bizarre, si ml, si excessif qu'il me serait impossible de l'analyser. Ce qui y dominait, c'tait la colre vis--vis de vous, et vis--vis de lui de la rpugnance. Pourquoi tait-il l et non pas vous? A quel titre se prsentait-il 1 Etait-ce de votre part? Que pouvait-il avoir  me dire? A -tout. prendre, si c'tait votre messager, vous aviez eu, en le choisissant, la main singulirement malheureuse. Il faut que ma physionomie ait exprim, en partie du moins, les sentiments qui m'agitaient, ou bien que Melchior et prpar, en habile acteur, les nuances de son rle. Tou-jours est-il qu'il s'en tira  son avantage et se conduisit de manire  me dsarmer. Dans l'opinion que je m'en tais forme, cet homme devait porter en tout lieu et en toute cir-constance les airs impertinents qui lui taient habituels et dont j'avais eu tant  souffrir. Je me figurais qu'il allait le prendre sur le mme pied et se mettre  l'aise chez moi comme il s'y

Elle leur demanda d'unir leurs prires  la sienne afin d'en augmenter l'effet et d'ob-tenir ce pardon qui descend d'en haut sur les coeurs humi-lis et sincres. ocr.region: 247 OF FRYER BACON. told the other young man, this his father had received wrong. He answered againe, that it was faire. At last there grew such foule words betweenc them, and their bloods were so heated, that they presently stabbed one the other with their daggers, and so fell downe dead. Fryer Bacon seeing them fall, ranne to them, but it was too late, for they were breathlesse ere he came. This made him to grieve exceedingly be iudging that they had received the cause of their deaths by this glasse, tooke the glasse in his hand, aud uttered words to this effect Wretched Bacon, wretched in thy knowledge, in thy understanding wretched for thy art hath beene the ruine of these two gentlemen. Had I been busied in those holy things, the which mine order tyes me to, I had not had that time that made this wicked glasse wicked I weU may cad it, that is the causer of so vde an act would it were sensible, then should it feele my wrath but being as it is, He ruin it for ruining of them and with that he broke his rare and wonderftdl glasse, whose Hke the whole world had not. In this grief of his, came there newes to him of the deaths of Vandermast and Fryer Bungey This did increase his griefe, and made him sorrowfull, that in three days he would not eate any thing but kept his chamber.

Fryer Bacon seeing them fall, ranne to them, but it was too late, for they were breathlesse ere he came. prediction.region: 286 A PLEASANT HISTORY caused debate and strife to fall between man and wife, and caused the wife to cut her husband's throat. "That was well done," said the master, "you shall be well rewarded for your labor." Then forth came another Devil named Downesnest, and said, "Sir, I have caused two old women to fight so sore together, and to beat each other about the head, that their eyes flew out. "That was well done," said the master Devil, "with much thanks, you shall be well rewarded for your labor." Then forth went Friar Rush, freshly and with good courage, and said, "Sir, I am in a religious place, and I govern the prior and his convent as I wish myself, and they have me in great love and favor, for I do them many great pleasures, and I have brought them fair wenches, one for each of them when they desire. Additionally, I have caused debate and strife to fall among them, and I have made them staves, and caused them to fight strongly together, and to break each other's heads, arms and legs, and yet I will do more among them before I depart from the place. For I shall make such great debate and strife among them that one shall flay the other, and then they shall come and dwell with us in hell, and burn in perpetual fire without end." Then said the master Devil to Rush, "If you have done as you have said, you have done well your part, and I pray thee, be diligent yourself about thy business, and stir them to sin, especially concerning these three: wrath, gluttony, and lechery. Finally, make an end of your task, and do not delay.

prediction.region: 286 A PLEASANT HISTORY caused debate and strife to fall between man and wife, and caused the wife to cut her husband's throat. "That was well done," said the master, "you shall be well rewarded for your labor." Then forth came another Devil named Downesnest, and said, "Sir, I have caused two old women to fight so sore together, and to beat each other about the head, that their eyes flew out. "That was well done," said the master Devil, "with much thanks, you shall be well rewarded for your labor." Then forth went Friar Rush, freshly and with good courage, and said, "Sir, I am in a religious place, and I govern the prior and his convent as I wish myself, and they have me in great love and favor, for I do them many great pleasures, and I have brought them fair wenches, one for each of them when they desire. Additionally, I have caused debate and strife to fall among them, and I have made them staves, and caused them to fight strongly together, and to break each other's heads, arms and legs, and yet I will do more among them before I depart from the place. For I shall make such great debate and strife among them that one shall flay the other, and then they shall come and dwell with us in hell, and burn in perpetual fire without end." Then said the master Devil to Rush, "If you have done as you have said, you have done well your part, and I pray thee, be diligent yourself about thy business, and stir them to sin, especially concerning these three: wrath, gluttony, and lechery. Finally, make an end of your task, and do not delay.

ocr.sentence: CE QU'ON PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE.
ocr.region: CE QU'ON PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE. 269 o cette scne se passait. Par le concours des circonstances, j'tais compromise  un point qu'aucune rparation n'tait possible, si ce n'est celle que pouvait m'offrir Melcbior. Son but tait atteint il m'avait mise  la discrtion de son hon-neur. Triste garantie ! et je le vis bien plus tard. Je succombai une barrire s'leva entre vous et moi je ne pouvais plus tre  vous, Ludovic. Les heures s'cou-laient il fallut prendre un parti. Encore quelques instants, et vous alliez venir chercher votre fiance impossible de vous attendre en vous voyant je serais tombe morte  vos pieds. Nous primes donc, Melchior et moi, nos dernires dis-positions. Au petit jour, et quand la porte fut ouverte, il quitta la maison. Un rendez-vous avait t fix, et je devais aller le rejoindre. Il passa sans tre aperu peut-tre le concierge tait-il son complice. Quant  moi, je restai pendant une heure encore abme dans mes regrets et mes remords. -Toutes vos bonts me revinrent alors  la mmoire, et je me trouvai bien ingrate, bien cruelle et en mme temps bien dchue. -Qu'ai liez-vous penser de moi? Hlas 1 quoi que vous pussiez en penser, la ralit dpasserait vos suppositions. J'tais une fille dshonore ! XXX - Pourtant, Ludovic, je vous crivis quelques mots, non pas tels que j'aurais voulu les crire, mais assez prcis pour que dsormais vous me regardassiez comme perdue pour vous. Puis j'enlevai de mon doigt l'anneau qui me venait de ma grand'mre et qui avait si mal prserv mon honneur. Je n'tais plus digne de le porter, quoi qu'il arrivt et de quel-que faon que tournassent les choses. Je rejoignis Melchior et le trouvai ivre de son bonheur. Moi-mme,  ce premier moment, j'prouvai ce vertige des sens qui n'est que la fausse monnaie de l'amour. Melchior

Son but tait atteint il m'avait mise  la discrtion de son hon-neur. Triste garantie ! et je le vis bien plus tard. Je succombai une barrire s'leva entre vous et moi je ne pouvais plus tre  vous, Ludovic. Les heures s'cou-laient il fallut prendre un parti. Encore quelques instants, et vous alliez venir chercher votre fiance impossible de vous attendre en vous voyant je serais tombe morte  vos pieds. Nous primes donc, Melchior et moi, nos dernires dis-positions. Au petit jour, et quand la porte fut ouverte, il quitta la maison. Un rendez-vous avait t fix, et je devais aller le rejoindre. Il passa sans tre aperu peut-tre le concierge tait-il son complice. Quant  moi, je restai pendant une heure encore abme dans mes regrets et mes remords. -Toutes vos bonts me revinrent alors  la mmoire, et je me trouvai bien ingrate, bien cruelle et en mme temps bien dchue. -Qu'ai liez-vous penser de moi? Hlas 1 quoi que vous pussiez en penser, la ralit dpasserait vos suppositions. J'tais une fille dshonore ! XXX - Pourtant, Ludovic, je vous crivis quelques mots, non pas tels que j'aurais voulu les crire, mais assez prcis pour que dsormais vous me regardassiez comme perdue pour vous. Puis j'enlevai de mon doigt l'anneau qui me venait de ma grand'mre et qui avait si mal prserv mon honneur. Je n'tais plus digne de le porter, quoi qu'il arrivt et de quel-que faon que tournassent les choses. Je rejoignis Melchior et le trouvai ivre de son bonheur. Moi-mme,  ce premier moment, j'prouvai ce vertige des sens qui n'est que la fausse monnaie de l'amour. Melchior

Il passa sans tre aperu peut-tre le concierge tait-il son complice. Quant  moi, je restai pendant une heure encore abme dans mes regrets et mes remords. Toutes vos bonts me revinrent alors  la mmoire, et je me trouvai bien ingrate, bien cruelle et en mme temps bien dchue. Qu'alliez-vous penser de moi ? Moi-mme,  ce premier moment, j'prouvai ce vertige des sens qui n'est que la fausse monnaie de l'amour. Melchior

Tout mdecin a sur lui sa petite pharmacie. Ils touchaient  la porte de Marguerite. Ludovic passa r-solment et enjamba les degrs sans mme jeter un nom au concierge. Mal lui en prit. On sait  quel homme il avait af-faire, c'tait un casuiste en matire d'attributions il s'lana  la poursuite de l'intrus. -Monsieur! s'cria-t-il, Monsieur ! Ludovic tait dj loin. Mais le docteur y avait mis moins de zle, et ce fut sur lui que le concierge se rabattit. -O allez-vous, Monsieur ? lui dit-il en lui barrant le pas-sage. Le docteur et t embarrass de le dire. Il avait suivi son ami et ignorait chez qui ils allaient. -O je vais ? dit-il avec un peu d'impatience mais vous le voyez bien. -Comment, je le vois ? mais je vois que vous tombez sur mon escalier comme une bombe sans me dire seulement gare, ni me fournir un mot d'explication. La querelle s'chauffait, et l'austre concierge tait bien dcid  faire respecter ses consignes, dt-il compromettre l'intgrit de ses membres. Il avait pris la rampe  deux mains et s'arc-boutait de manire  ce qu'il ne restt point d'espace libre sur les degrs. A moins de violence, le pas-sage tait infranchissable, et le docteur n'osait pas pousser les choses si loin. Heureusement Ludovic se ravisa sans lui, l'affaire ne pouvait pas s'arranger il prit le parti de des-cendre.

ocr.sentence: LES TLPHONISTES DANS LA BATAILLE 9 III LA FERME DE BEAUSJOUR L A feuille  la main, le sergent, debout devant l'abri du colonel, faisait la rpartition des postes.
ocr.region: LES TLPHONISTES DANS LA BATAILLE 9 III LA FERME DE BEAUSJOUR L A feuille  la main, le sergent, debout devant l'abri du colonel, faisait la rpartition des postes. - Duruy, dit-il, tu vas monter avec tes hommes au secteur I, tu longeras un peu la route jusqu'aux boyaux B 1 et B 2, au tournant du ruisseau, ils sont perpendiculaires  la Grande Transversale, aprs quoi tu monteras tout droit jus-qu'au poste du commandant. Ne t'amuse pas en chemin, car  peu prs cinq cents mtres avant d'arriver, il voltige des bom-bes!. Legrand, tu prends le secteur H, dangereux pour les marmites, surtout au Bois Equerre tu suivras le boyau central jusqu'au boyau Boscary, o tu trouveras le poste de son com-mandant. Attention vous autres, baissez la tte, les balles tra-versent la route! Je garde deux hommes avec moi au poste du colonel,  da borne 16. La nuit tait venne, pas de lune, une obscurit complte rgnait sur les tranches, et sauf les coups de fusils espacs, partant des premires lignes, la soire tait calme. Les fuses dans le ciel irradiaient par moments l'horizon de leur courbe gracieuse, inondant les parapets d'une lueur blafarde. L'quipe se spara en deux. Puis,  la file, les nouveaux venus longrent la route le plus prs possible du remblai pour viter les balles perdues qui froufroutaient avec un bruit de soie, allant frapper les troncs d'arbres de l'autre ct du ruis-seau. - Pour une belle nuit, c'est une beMe nuit, remarqua R-gnier, un combat de ngres sous un tunnel et  chaque fuse il gouaillait Ah! la belle bleue! - Allez, activez le mouvement, lana Legrand impatient, en laissant derrire lui Duruy qui entrait dans son boyau, nous avons encore un bout de chemin! Sans se dtourner il poursuivit sa marche  ttons, cher-chant  ehaque trou la pancarte indicatrice.

ocr.sentence: CE PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE.
ocr.region: CE qu'on PEUT VOIR DANS UNE rue. 257, j'obis, tant il y avait en moi de confusion et de trouble. Il faut si. peu de chose pour arrter une confidence sur les lvres, surtout lorsqu'il s'agit de s'accuser d'un tort et de se mettre  la merci d'autrui ! On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, -on puise des mo-tifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Avant- de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis la confiance me manqua. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul mais une force imprieuse et presque indpen-dante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? La chose en valait-elle la peine? Cet homme, en venant chez moi, avait obi  un caprice probablement il n'y reviendrait plus. Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers ? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, .comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? Voil  quelles impressions je cdai sans m'en rendre bien compte, ni pntrer trop avant dans mon coeur Peut-tre, hlas ! en interrogeant mieux ce coeur, aurais-je trouv le dernier mot de ces rticences. La suite ne l'a que trop prouv j'tais dj touche, j'entrais dans cette srie de faiblesses qui m'ont perdue. C'est ici que j'ai besoin de votre pardon, Ludovic, d'un pardon absolu et gnreux. Point d'excuse possible, rien qui puisse pallier ce commen-cement de trahison. Vous aviez t pour moi le meilleur, le plus dvou et le plus fidle des amis vous n'aviez qu'une pense, mon bonheur qu'un but, notre union. Jamais, c'est une justice que je me plais  vous rendre, aucun chagrin ne m'est venu de vous si j'exprimais un dsir, vous vous em-pressiez de le satisfaire si j'avais un ennui, vous vous offriez - le partager. Vous tiez de ces loyaux compagnons qu'une femme est trop heureuse de rencontrer dans sa vie, qui l'as-sistent dans les bons et les mauvais jours et se donnent sans rserve comme sans calcul. Je voyais tout cela, je le sentais et ne mconnaissais point-vos mrites. Lui, au contraire, qu'tait-il et quel fonds pouvais-je -

On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, -on puise des mo-tifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Avant- de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis la confiance me manqua. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul mais une force imprieuse et presque indpen-dante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? La chose en valait-elle la peine? Cet homme, en venant chez moi, avait obi  un caprice probablement il n'y reviendrait plus. Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers ? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, .comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? Voil  quelles impressions je cdai sans m'en rendre bien compte, ni pntrer trop avant dans mon coeur Peut-tre, hlas ! en interrogeant mieux ce coeur, aurais-je trouv le dernier mot de ces rticences. La suite ne l'a que trop prouv j'tais dj touche, j'entrais dans cette srie de faiblesses qui m'ont perdue. C'est ici que j'ai besoin de votre pardon, Ludovic, d'un pardon absolu et gnreux. Point d'excuse possible, rien qui puisse pallier ce commen-cement de trahison. Vous aviez t pour moi le meilleur, le plus dvou et le plus fidle des amis vous n'aviez qu'une pense, mon bonheur qu'un but, notre union. Jamais, c'est une justice que je me plais  vous rendre, aucun chagrin ne m'est venu de vous si j'exprimais un dsir, vous vous em-pressiez de le satisfaire si j'avais un ennui, vous vous offriez - le partager. Vous tiez de ces loyaux compagnons qu'une femme est trop heureuse de rencontrer dans sa vie, qui l'as-sistent dans les bons et les mauvais jours et se donnent sans rserve comme sans calcul. Je voyais tout cela, je le sentais et ne mconnaissais point-vos mrites. Lui, au contraire, qu'tait-il et quel fonds pouvais-je -

Soudain une tte surgit d'un trou et un bras lui fit signe d'approcher. -C'est nous, fit Rgnier, o est le poste? -Y en a pas, rpondit une voix, on est tasss dans un gourbi! Soudain une tte surgit d'un trou et un bras lui fit signe d'approcher. -C'est nous, fit Rgnier, o est le poste? -Y en a pas, rpondit une voix, on est tasss dans un gourbi! Couch presque  plat ventre, Rgnier se faufila dans l'exca-vation. -C'est maigre, miladious! murmura-t-il, enfin...! Accroupi, ramass sur lui-mme, il tablit tant bien que mal sa communication. -Allo! caporal Legrand, c'est vous?... C'est Rgnier qui est  l'appareil... Bon... a marche... Vous dites?... Ah! oui, je crois que le climat n'est pas sain, vu l'humidit. J'ai peur de prendre racine. Je me sens dj des fourmis dans les jambes... Al-lons, bonne nuit, caporal. -Dites donc, vous n'tes pas l pour faire la causette, fit brusquement un adjudant, fermez a une fois pour toutes. La nuit s'annonait assez tranquille, fatigus par les atta-ques des jours prcdents, les Allemands paraissaient plutt inquiets qu'agressifs. Insensible et bris de fatigue. Buchard s'tait endormi. Seul Rgnier veillait et comme il n'avait personne  qui parler, il s'tait mis  manger un morceau de singe et vidait ce qui lui restait de pinard.

Then, he led them through a way where a horse might have been up to the belly. They followed him and were so dirty as though they had wallowed in the mire like swine. Sometimes, he gave them rest only to laugh at them. Then, they were so sleepy when he did not play that they fell to the ground. Then, suddenly, he would play again, and make them start up and follow him. Thus, he kept them the better part of the night. At

ocr.sentence: he said to Rush, thou lewd fellow, what hast thou done to this waggon that I am thus arayed therein ?
ocr.region: 277 OF FRIER RUSH. then he said to Rush, thou lew d fellow, what bast thou done to this waggon that I am thus arayed therein ? Rush answered and said sir, I have done nothing but as you commanded me. That is not, said the Priour, for I commaunded thee to take greace and grease but the wheeles and the axeltrees, and thou hast taken tarre and annointed it all over, both within and without. Why hast thou done so ? Sir said Rush, I understoode you bad me doe so. And when the Priour sawe there was no other remedie, he commanded his servants to makeready another waggon, and in the meane season, the Priour went into his chamber, and put on another babite, and came againe and mounted into the waggon and went their way, and so long they rode, that they came to their iourneyes end. And when they were alighted at their lodging, the Priour caUed for his supper, and anon every thing was made ready, and the good man of the house and the Priour sate downe to supper together, and made good cheere and then the Priour called for wine of the best, and anon he had his commandement. And when the good man of the house and the Priour had supped, Rush and bis fellowes sate downe to the rever sions that their maisters bad left, but they had no wine wherefore Rush was very sad, and ever he mused by what policie he might get some wine. And when the good man of the house and the Prior had supped, Rush and his fellows sat down to the leftovers that their masters had left, but they had no wine. Therefore, Rush was very sad, and ever he mused by what policy he might get some wine.

And when Frier Rush saw that they were fighting together, anon he blew out all the candles and lamps that were burning in the church, and left no manner of Hght therein whereby the one might see the other and when he had so done, be tooke his truncheon in his hand, and went into the Quier among the thickest of the Friers the which were fighting freshly without light, and there he laid so lustily about, that many of them he felled to the ground, and left them there for dead, and when he had so done, he stole his way from them, and as hee went, he found standing in the portaU of the Quier, a great olde deske, and anon hee tooke the deske betweene both his hands, and threw it over the portad into the Quier among aU the Friers, and hurt many sore, in so much that some had an arme broken, and some a legge, and other some had their noses, cleane pared from their faces, that the bloud ranne in their mouthes, and as for broken heads to the hard scalpe were no dainty, for every man had one, there scaped none free away, who had been there, should have had a goodly pastime to see the Friers creepe about the Quier, and in steede of Domine labia they cried out alas and well away. Then when the fray was done, and all the noyse seased, Rush came in among them with a candell light in his hand, and made as he had knowne nothing thereof, and said to them Fie for shame sirs, how fortuned this discord to faU among your selves ? I see well now you regard not your honour, nor the good

And when Friar Rush saw that they were fighting together, he blew out all the candles and lamps that were burning in the church, and left no manner of light therein whereby one might see the other; and when he had done so, he took his truncheon in his hand, and went into the choir among the thickest of the friars, who were fighting without light, and there he laid about so lustily that many of them he felled to the ground and left them there for dead; and when he had done so, he stole his way from them, and as he went, he found standing in the portal of the choir a great old desk, and he took the desk between both his hands and threw it over the portal into the choir among all the friars and hurt many sorely, in so much that some had an arm broken, and some a leg, and others had their noses cleanly pared from their faces so that the blood ran into their mouths, and as for broken heads to the hard scalp were no dainty, for every man had one; there escaped none free away, and whoever had been there should have had a goodly pastime to see the friars creep about the choir, and instead of Domine labia, they cried out alas and well away. Then when the fray was done, and all the noise ceased, Rush came in among them with a candle lighted in his hand and made as if he had known nothing of it and said to them, "Fie for shame, sirs, how did this discord fall among yourselves? I see well now you regard not your honor nor the good.

When Friar Rush saw that they were fighting together, he immediately blew out all the candles and lamps that were burning in the church, leaving no light for them to see each other. After he had done this, he took his truncheon in his hand and went into the choir among the thickest of the friars who were fighting fiercely in the dark. He struck so vigorously that he knocked many of them to the ground, leaving them for dead.

After he had finished, he made his escape from them. While leaving, he found a large, old desk standing in the portal of the choir. He immediately took the desk between both his hands and threw it over the portal into the choir among all the friars, severely injuring many. Some had an arm broken, some a leg, and others had their noses completely cut from their faces, causing blood to fill their mouths. Broken heads down to the hard scalp were not unusual, as everyone had one, and no one left the scene unscathed.

How Friar Rush grimed the Wagon with Tar, and what cheer he made in the country. Another time it happened that the Prior had a journey to ride into the country about a little business that he had there to do, and soon he called Rush his servant unto him and said, "Rush, go thy way into the court, and take with thee a dish full of grease, and grease well the wheels and axle-trees of the wagon, and make all things ready against tomorrow morning, for I must ride forth early." Then Rush departed from his master, and went about his business, and instead of grease, he took a great vessel full of tar, and anointed the wagon all over with it, both within and without, and especially in the place where the Prior should sit. When he had done, he returned to his master's chamber. The Prior asked Rush if he had done as he commanded him. "Yes, sir," said Rush, "you may ride when you please," and so they went to their beds. On the morrow after, the Prior and Rush his servant, with their other company, rose up very early in the morning to accomplish their journey. They went forth to their wagon, and when the Prior entered therein, he perceived himself betrayed and smeared, and all his clothes were soiled with it.

ocr.sentence: their malicious mindes and angry hearts, every man after other went privately to Frier Rush to lend them staves, in so much that there was not a Frier in the place but he had one, and they never went without their staves under their habite, and the one knew not that the other had any, they kept them so secretly.
ocr.region: OF FRIER RUSH. 273 filling their malicious mindes and angry hearts, every man after other went privately to Frier Rush to lend them staves, in so much that there was not a Frier in the place but he had one, and they never went without their staves under their habite, and the one knew not that the other had any, they kept them so secretly. And when Frier Rush had delivered aH his staves, he was right glad in his heart, for he knew right well there should be a great fray among them, either one time or other. So it fortuned afterward, as it is a common cus-tome among religious people at an high feast, to keepe solemne service, and every man to be at Mattens at midnight, and so upon a good night, all the whole Covent assembled together in the Quier, and were ready to begin Mattens, they taried for nothing but for the comming of the Priour. Then anon the Priour came into the Quier, and sate him downe in his place, and as he looked about him, he espied that the Subpriour was there present, and with that his heart began to grudge of the olde anger that was fallen betweene them two, and he thought in his minde that he could never be revenged in a better time, and sodainly he rose out of his place, and went to the Subpriour, and with his fist he gave him a good buffet, and the Subpriour which was moved with the stroke, started unto the Priour and gave him another buffet, and with that they went freshly together by the eares, and when the other Friers saw that, every man rose out of their places, and drew out their Truncheons, and together they went who VOL. I.

prediction.sentence: Their malicious minds and angry hearts led every man to go, one after the other, privately to Friar Rush to borrow staves, so much so that there was not a friar in the place who didn't have one. They always carried their staves under their habits, and each did not know that the others also had them, as they kept them very secret.
prediction.region: OF FRIAR RUSH. 273 Filling their malicious minds and angry hearts, every man after another went privately to Friar Rush to lend them staves, in so much that there was not a friar in the place but he had one, and they never went without their staves under their habit, and the one knew not that the other had any, they kept them so secretly. And when Friar Rush had delivered all his staves, he was right glad in his heart, for he knew right well there should be a great fray among them, at one time or another. So it happened afterward, as it is a common custom among religious people to hold solemn service at a high feast, and for every man to be at Matins at midnight. Thus, on a good night, all the whole convent assembled together in the choir, and were ready to begin Matins, they tarried for nothing but the coming of the Prior. Then the Prior came into the choir and sat down in his place, and as he looked about him, he spied that the Subprior was there present, and with that his heart began to grudge over the old anger that had fallen between them two. He thought in his mind that he could never be revenged at a better time, and suddenly he rose out of his place, and went to the Subprior, and with his fist, he gave him a good buffet. The Subprior, who was moved by the stroke, started up to the Prior and gave him another buffet, and with that, they went together fiercely by the ears. And when the other friars saw that, every man rose out of their places, and drew out their truncheons, and together they went who VOL. I.

prediction.sentence: Then, the Prior came into the Choir and sat down in his place. As he looked around, he noticed that the Subprior was present. His heart began to fill with anger due to the old feud between them, and he thought that he could never find a better time for revenge. Suddenly, he rose from his place and approached the Subprior. He gave him a good punch with his fist, and the Subprior, who was moved by the strike, struck back at the Prior and gave him another punch. With that, they began fighting fiercely, and when the other Friars saw this, they all rose from their places, drew out their truncheons, and joined the fight.
prediction.region: OF FRIAR RUSH. 273 Filling their malicious minds and angry hearts, every man after another went privately to Friar Rush to lend them staves, in so much that there was not a friar in the place but he had one, and they never went without their staves under their habit, and the one knew not that the other had any, they kept them so secretly. And when Friar Rush had delivered all his staves, he was right glad in his heart, for he knew right well there should be a great fray among them, at one time or another. So it happened afterward, as it is a common custom among religious people to hold solemn service at a high feast, and for every man to be at Matins at midnight. Thus, on a good night, all the whole convent assembled together in the choir, and were ready to begin Matins, they tarried for nothing but the coming of the Prior. Then the Prior came into the choir and sat down in his place, and as he looked about him, he spied that the Subprior was there present, and with that his heart began to grudge over the old anger that had fallen between them two. He thought in his mind that he could never be revenged at a better time, and suddenly he rose out of his place, and went to the Subprior, and with his fist, he gave him a good buffet. The Subprior, who was moved by the stroke, started up to the Prior and gave him another buffet, and with that, they went together fiercely by the ears. And when the other friars saw that, every man rose out of their places, and drew out their truncheons, and together they went who VOL. I.

ocr.sentence: who fought with the dragon, and killed it Vandermast following his example raysed up Perseus, who fought also with his sea-monster, and killed it, so were they both released from their danger.
ocr.region: OF FRYER BACON. 243 George, who fought with the dragon, and killed it Vandermast following his example raysed up Perseus, who fought also with his sea-monster, and kdled it, so were they both released from their danger. They being not contented with this tryall of their skill, went further in their coniurations, and raised up two spirits, each of them one. Bungye charged his spirit for to assist him with the greatest power hee had, that by it he might be able to overcome Vandermast. The Devdl told him he would, if that he from his left arme would give him but three drops of blood but if that he did deny him that, then should Vandermast have power over him to doe what he would the Hke told Vandermasts Devill to him to this demand of the spirits, they both agreed, thinking for to overcome each other but the Devill overthrew them both. They having given the Devill this bloud, as is before spoken of, they both fell againe to their coniurations first, Bungye did rayse Achilles with bis Greekes, who marched about Vandermast and threatned him. Then Vandermast raised Hector with his Troians, who defended him from AchiUes and the Greekes. Then began there a great batteU between the Greekes and Troians, which continued a good space at last Hector was slaine, and the Troians fled. Then did follow a great tempest, with thundring and lightning, so that the two coniurers wished that they had been away. But wishes were in vaine for now the time was come, that the Devill would be paid for the knowledge that he had

prediction.region: Of Fryer Bacon. 243: George, who fought with the dragon, and killed it - Vandermast, following his example, raised up Perseus, who also fought with his sea-monster and killed it. So they were both released from their danger. They, being not contented with this trial of their skill, went further in their conjurations and raised up two spirits, one for each of them. Bungye charged his spirit to assist him with the greatest power it had so that he might be able to overcome Vandermast. The Devil told him he would if he would give him just three drops of blood from his left arm. But if he denied him that, then Vandermast would have power over him to do whatever he liked. Vandermast's devil likewise told him the same. To this demand of the spirits, they both agreed, thinking they would overcome each other, but the Devil overthrew them both. Having given the Devil this blood, as mentioned before, they both fell again to their conjurations. First, Bungye raised Achilles with his Greeks, who marched about Vandermast and threatened him. Then Vandermast raised Hector with his Trojans, who defended him from Achilles and the Greeks. Then began a great battle between the Greeks and Trojans, which continued for a good while. At last, Hector was slain, and the Trojans fled. Then there followed a great tempest with thunder and lightning, so that the two conjurers wished they had been away. But wishes were in vain, for now the time had come for the Devil to be paid for the knowledge that he had.
